{"response":{"status":"ok","userTier":"internal","total":96270,"startIndex":1,"pageSize":20,"currentPage":1,"pages":4814,"orderBy":"newest","tag":{"webTitle":"Books","id":"books/books","sectionId":"books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},"results":[{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-17T13:00:09Z","webTitle":"Wanted: original book titles","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/feb/17/wanted-original-book-titles","fields":{"commentable":"false","byline":"Valentine","headline":"Wanted: original book titles","trailText":"It’s hard not to judge a book by its title when they’re all so unimaginative, says <strong>site member Valentine</strong>. What is this trend for dramatic one-word titles that don’t really mean anything all about?","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>On a recent trip to my local bookstore, I couldn’t help but notice that the young adult shelves are becoming increasingly populated by books with slightly obscure single-word titles: Divergent, Slated, Delirium, Cinder, Angelfire (this one is two words smooshed together into a one word title!). The titles began to blur together as I started to wonder, what has happened to original book naming? </p> <p>I don’t want to criticise any of these books for their title alone, many of those I reference in this article are books I haven’t read so I’m not judging the content at all, but why do so many YA books have to succumb to this trend? Wouldn’t it be better to make your book stand out by giving it a more memorable title which didn’t seem like it was lifted from a dictionary of unusual words in a desperate attempt to sound unique? I love interesting words as much as the next person and I love to use them in stories but when I look at a shelf full of these single-word titles I find them rather formulaic.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/20/trendy-following-the-crowd-teen-books\">'Trendy' books: should we really be following the crowd?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Then there are the not-so-unique single-word titles, the ones that don’t even try to be unusual. They sometimes end in -ed and, much as I hate to admit being so judgemental, they are an easy way to make sure I never even pick up the book. Matched, Switched, Fallen, Uglies (or its sequels Pretties, Extras and Specials)... All potentially brilliant books but the titles are enough to send me to sleep. Maybe the one-word title was simple and effective when Jane Austen wrote Persuasion but now there’s nothing like one of these titles to make your book seem like “just another teen novel”, regardless of what an amazing story you may have written.</p> <p>To make matters worse, all these books seem to have endless sequels, with increasingly nonsensical titles in an attempt to make them match. Why do they have to match?! The matching title trend is driving me to distraction! Divergent fans may hate me for saying this, but for me, rhyming series titles are equivalent to naming your twins Ronald and Donald! </p> <p>Unwind, UnStrung, UnWholly, UnSouled, UnDivided, UnBound... Surely this is taking the matching title trend a step too far. Those mid-word capital letters aren’t doing anything for me either. UnSouled isn’t even a real word – perhaps there ought to be a companion volume called “UnGrammatical”!</p> <p>Not all of these matching series titles are single-word of course: Shatter Me, Unravel Me, Ignite Me, Destroy Me and Fracture Me made me cringe almost as much as Matched, Crossed and Reached (Reached? As in I “reached” for the only book on the shelf with an original title only to find it had two sequels that rhymed?) Then there’s Slated, Shattered and Fractured – sound familiar?</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/14/only-in-ya-teen-books\">Only in YA</a> </p> </aside>  <p>I don’t want to stop anyone enjoying these books or deny that many of these are popular novels with many devoted readers. Perhaps this is just a pet peeve of mine but I can’t help sighing with relief when I find a series that doesn’t feel the need to prove that the books belong together by making them sound the same. Fortunately for me, there are noble exceptions to this trend: the Miss Peregrine’s Peculiar Children trilogy and the Chaos Walking trilogy to name a couple. No doubt “don’t judge a book by its title” will be the resounding roar, just don’t expect me to be picking up The Selection any time soon (or its sequels The Elite, The One, The Heir, The Crown and on and on and on........)</p> <h2><strong>Are you burning with desire to express your <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/series/teen-opinion\">teen opinion</a> on a book-related subject? <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site here if you’re a keen reader and not already a member!</a></strong></h2>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4g789","wordcount":"643","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/86ffa16610bf47194c2b865482f10e5d40a83127/0_154_2187_1312/140.jpg","standfirst":"<p>It’s hard not to judge a book by its title when they’re all so unimaginative, says <strong>site member Valentine</strong>. What is this trend for dramatic one-word titles that don’t really mean anything all about?</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/17/wanted-original-book-titles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/17/wanted-original-book-titles","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"86ffa16610bf47194