"type":"blog","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Teen books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/series/author-opinion","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Author opinion","type":"series","description":"Find out what your favourite authors think about life and books – and everything in between","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/series/author-opinion","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/series/author-opinion","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-17T07:30:16Z","webTitle":"No Way But Gentlenesse by Richard Hines review – life with Kes the kestrel","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/feb/17/no-way-but-gentlenesse-a-memoir-of-how-kes-my-kestrel-changed-my-life-richard-hines-review-memoir","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Tim Dee","headline":"No Way But Gentlenesse by Richard Hines review – life with Kes the kestrel","trailText":"Barry Hines wrote the book that became Ken Loach’s film, but it was Richard, his brother, who caught and trained the kestrels. It changed him forever, and now finally he tells his story","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>For much of the last 100 years, before the buzzard barrelled out of the north and west to become the commonest raptor in Britain, our most familiar bird of prey was the kestrel. These small falcons secured their passage into the modern world by learning to exploit the grassed cuttings and embankments of motorways and main roads. There they hover and scour the terrain beneath them for their rodent prey. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/gerard-manley-hopkins\">Gerard Manley Hopkins</a>’s poem <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2010/apr/01/windhover-gerard-manley-hopkins\">“The Windhover”</a> describes this action superbly well. “Wind-fucker” was another old name for the bird.</p> <p>But this hunting technique, their breathtaking ability to stop in the air, as well as their relatively small size and unglamorous diet, meant kestrels were little valued in falconry. The sport aped raptor taxonomy and devised its own spurious pedigree. The top of the human social ladder were supposed to take on the most charismatic avian hunters, emperors trained eagles and princes peregrines, while those on the bottom rungs, the ‘knaves’, had to make do with kestrels.</p> <p>One of Richard Hines’s skills as a teenage falconer in the 1960s, alongside his ability to rear and keep several wild kestrel fledglings that he took from their nests, was to turn the knave’s bird into a stooping falcon via his self-taught knack with a lure (scraps of meat tied to a weighted pad and swung on a line, as a lassoing cowboy might, close enough to the falcon to entice it to follow but not so close that it might catch at the meat). “Come on, Kes,” he’d call and the birds did his bidding.</p> <p>If this already sounds familiar it is thanks to Hines. It was his life with his kestrels that inspired his older brother Barry to write the novel <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/kestrel-for-a-knave-3.html\"><em>A Kestrel for a Knave</em></a> in 1968, which in turn led to Ken Loach’s film <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/kes\"><em>Kes</em></a> in 1969. Barry Hines wrote the screenplay for the film with Loach and the producer Tony Garnett; Richard Hines trained the three kestrels that starred alongside <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0103193/\">David (now Dai) Bradley</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/nov/03/colin-welland\">Colin Welland</a> and <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0323093/\">Brian Glover</a>. The book has been widely taught in schools and reissued as a modern classic; the film, beautifully performed, moving and funny, is among the most successful of Loach’s, and almost certainly his most popular.</p> <p>Hines’s memoir comes to the story slightly late in the day and somewhat apologetically. It is not quite sure whether it wants to correct what we know and push his name up the ladder of the credits, or, with more generous intentions, to show a deeper and more extended truth around the fictions. I think it is a bit of both. Nonetheless, it is certainly worth having. And its plain-spoken and unflashy but eloquent account, as its title suggests, of all sorts of gentleness, first to do with the taming of meat-eating raptors, but then also related to Hines’s human kith and kin, runs deep into the literature of birds and people: the seeing through birds that some people crave – an understanding of how the world works – and the way those people are simultaneously seen through – sustained and nurtured – by those same birds.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>We are reminded that those who have sought out these birds of prey have often been wounded or troubled</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>Hines was born in 1945 and brought up in the pit village of Hoyland Common south of Barnsley. Its deep-dug black coal was hauled to the surface among green fields. A grandfather died in a mine accident and his father began his working life aged 14 as a pit-pony driver: he was wounded with a gash to his head that filled with coal dust leaving him with a permanent scar “as deep blue as a tattoo”. Life was hard. The toilet they shared with their neighbours was 30 yards from their door. Deaths and injuries in the colliery marked all village life. And failure, too, soon came to call. Barry got into a grammar school but “halfwit” Richard was shunted towards the terminus of a secondary modern. Then he saw a kestrel hovering nearby, “so aloof, so wild”, and, as it has to in books such as this, his world was turned over and he was “captivated” by “wildness” – “I knew that I’d love to bring one into my life,” he writes.</p> <p>Richard takes a kestrel from its nest. There is no one to tell him what to do next: falconry is for posh people. He copies out a hawking book he finds in the reference section of his library, and plans to cannibalise a pair of his mother’s leather gloves for jesses (straps). I doesn’t go swimmingly. The first kestrel died when being cared for by Barry. Richard stalls at times and forfeits chances to escape the cage of his youth. He wins prizes and comes top of the class, moves to the grammar and captains its rugby team, but quits and repeatedly sabotages himself, while Barry is always ahead of him, in his V-necked sweater with its sleeves pushed up, getting on. Meanwhile, their dad dies, his “kind, gentle face” looking out from his open coffin.</p> <p>Hines’s sweet title comes from a 17th-century falconry manual. And gentleness sweetly pushes through much of his book, with the words kind and gentle oozing a little too obviously and too often from its pages.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"55fef94697d6a5137c064a94574a8be793158fb9\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/55fef94697d6a5137c064a94574a8be793158fb9/0_0_2432_4320/563.jpg\" alt=\"Richard Hines\" width=\"563\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Richard Hines, the real-life Billy Casper</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Hines tamed himself at last and made a success of his life thanks to his skills at manning his falcons. He grew up and became a teacher and a documentary film-maker. His parents, brother and friends were mostly kind to him. A Nigerian schoolboy he taught on a VSO secondment was kind; so were the women supporters of the miners’ strikes he made films about.</p> <p>Something falters once again in the final third of the book. After the hazards and excitement of training kestrels for the camera, and the thrill of seeing his own skills (his gentleness and love) acknowledged in a novel and on screen, Hines backs out of his story. He became a vegetarian, having read <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/ethics-of-what-we-eat.html\">Peter Singer</a>, and he stopped keeping falcons (though there is a beautiful coda of a last merlin learning to catch its own meadow pipits). Hines’s brother went on to write more novels and screenplays but disappears before the end the book. And the book itself comes to a halt, riven with unsorted class and status anxieties that refresh old scars. Perhaps Hines’s mother preferred her first son. Perhaps that son never was able to see his younger brother for what he was. Nor could falconry ever offer a real escape: the knave seems doomed to remain a knave no matter how adroitly he handles his kestrel. Meeting a more privileged falconer brings home to Hines the hierarchies of power intrinsic to the sport. And we are reminded that those who have sought out these birds of prey have often been wounded or troubled or have sick souls. Hines mentions the influence of two great but damaged texts: TH White’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/309430/\"><em>The Goshawk</em> </a>and JA Baker’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/peregrine.html\"><em>The Peregrine</em></a>. And, inevitably, there are passages in his book that will remind readers of Helen Macdonald’s 2014 prize-winning memoir <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/h-is-for-hawk.html\"><em>H Is for Hawk</em></a>.</p> <p>Falconry often has sad ends – Macdonald’s Mabel, who had done so much to mend her falconer, dies of an infection in an aviary; White’s goshawk flees its keeper, dragging its ensnaring jesses behind it; even Baker’s soft-footed stalk of a sleeping wild peregrine is black-rimmed with a sense of a sick man approaching a sickly bird. Hines’s best end is different from these and isn’t where his book finishes. It is in the fleetingly mentioned fact that – unlike those moribund hawks and falcons – all the kestrels that he successfully reared and flew were hacked back after a season or a year, returned to the wild and restored to their lives. The gentleness that had kept them also let them go.</p> <p>• Tim Dee’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/four-fields-2.html\"><em>Four Fields</em></a> is published by Vintage. To order<strong> </strong><em>No Way But Gentlenesse</em> (RRP £18.99) for £15.19 go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/377328/s/no-way-but-gentlenesse//?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","