_5371/8955.jpg","width":"8955","height":"5371"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/c00f943ed898ff0b8969d1a18b787a68aac190fd/0_1368_8955_5371/master/8955.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/c00f943ed898ff0b8969d1a18b787a68aac190fd","altText":"Vincent Brings Plenty, Star Village from Lost in the Wilderness by Kalpesh Lathigra","source":"Kalpesh Lathigra","mediaId":"c00f943ed898ff0b8969d1a18b787a68aac190fd","displayCredit":"true","photographer":"Kalpesh Lathigra","credit":"Photograph: Kalpesh Lathigra","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/c00f943ed898ff0b8969d1a18b787a68aac190fd/0_1368_8955_5371/master/8955.jpg","width":"8955","height":"5371","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"artanddesign/photography","sectionId":"artanddesign","webTitle":"Photography","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/photography","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/photography","sectionName":"Art and design","references":[]},{"id":"artanddesign/artanddesign","sectionId":"artanddesign","webTitle":"Art and design","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/artanddesign","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/artanddesign","sectionName":"Art and design","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"world/native-americans","sectionId":"us-news","webTitle":"Native Americans","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/native-americans","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/native-americans","sectionName":"US news","references":[]},{"id":"us-news/us-news","sectionId":"us-news","webTitle":"US news","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/us-news","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/us-news/us-news","sectionName":"US news","references":[]},{"id":"world/indigenous-peoples","sectionId":"world","webTitle":"Indigenous peoples","type":"keyword","description":"Latest news on Indigenous people across the world. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/indigenous-australians\">Click here for more on Indigenous Australians</a>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/indigenous-peoples","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/indigenous-peoples","sectionName":"World news","references":[]},{"id":"world/world","sectionId":"world","webTitle":"World news","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/world","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/world","sectionName":"World news","references":[]},{"id":"books/art","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Art and design","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/art","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/art","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/gallery","webTitle":"Gallery","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/inpictures","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/gallery","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-17T03:56:49Z","webTitle":"This is Australia's first picture book about married same-sex parents – why did it take so long?","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/feb/17/this-is-australias-first-picture-book-about-same-sex-parenting-why-did-it-take-so-long","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Steph Harmon","headline":"This is Australia's first picture book about married same-sex parents – why did it take so long?","trailText":"Created by Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter, Mummy and Mumma Get Married follows the attempt of a young girl to surprise her parents with a wedding. The only thing stopping them is you-know-who","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"AUS","body":"<p>A young girl, Phoebe, is curious. Her favourite football player is about to get married, joining a long line of other married couples in her life. So why didn’t her parents ever have a wedding?</p> <p>She asks them. </p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>“We’d love to be married,” said Mummy. </p> <p>“But what about you-know-who? We can’t have a wedding until they agree to come to the party,” Mumma said to Mummy.</p> <p>Phoebe didn’t know who you-know-who was. She decided to go ahead and organise a surprise wedding for her mummies anyway.</p> </blockquote> <p>Thus begins Mummy and Mumma Get Married, a children’s book by Byron Bay couple Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter, with illustrations by Cara King, which was crowdfunded to completion earlier this year. Although Hopkins and Winter both have a background in the industry – they met at a publishing office – it’s their first book together. And although there are other Australian children’s picture books that feature alternative family types, from their knowledge it’s the first book in Australia to specifically focus on same-sex parents. </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--supporting\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/gallery/2016/feb/17/great-childrens-picture-books-about-same-sex-parenting-in-pictures\">Great children's picture books about same-sex parenting – in pictures</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Hopkins was surprised by the gap in the market, particularly compared with the US and the UK, where these types of books are much more common. “I suppose maybe it’s just a reflection of how behind the eight ball on the topic we are in Australia,” she says.</p> <p>Mummy and Mumma Get Married was conceived by Hopkins while she was trying to get her daughter, Dexie, to sleep, on 22 May – the same night as the Irish referendum after which that country became the first to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/23/gay-marriage-ireland-yes-vote\">legalise same-sex marriage by popular vote</a>. Under the conservative prime ministership of Tony Abbott, meanwhile, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/28/the-guardian-view-on-australia-and-gay-marriage-all-out-of-step-except-tony-abbott\">Australia seemed to be moving backwards</a> on the issue. “I was thinking about [my daughter] and how it would feel from her perspective, and how I wanted her to feel that she came from a structure that was recognised and validated.” Hopkins shared her idea with Dexie’s other mother the next day, and Winter started writing immediately. “I was at work, I came home, and she’d done it.” </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"8f415717b73f701b9f305a931d69cc14e0a56870\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/8f415717b73f701b9f305a931d69cc14e0a56870/0_0_2398_1381/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Mummy and Mumma get Married (2016)\" width=\"1000\" height=\"576\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Spread from Mummy and Mumma Get Married, by Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter, with illustrations by Cara King.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Cara King/Captain Honey</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The story follows Phoebe’s attempt to organise a surprise wedding for her mothers, inviting their friends and family, while retaining a hope that “you-know-who” shows up. </p> <p>“We had to change that in production,” Hopkins laughs. “The text originally read ‘a certain someone’, and it was much clearer that that ‘certain someone’ was Tony Abbott. The ending was a little bit different too, because this certain someone was always ‘late to the party’. It was a very deliberate pun on him.” </p> <p>But then the 2015 leadership spill happened, and the book had to change. “At the beginning I was thinking ‘how am I gonna do this?’ ... But as we began to think about ‘you-know-who’, it became much clearer to me that actually, while the political parties, the prime minister and those institutions of power and authority do provide obstacles, there’s also somebody in most people’s lives who is a you-know-who – it might be a father, a grandmother, an uncle. It could be anybody.”</p> <p>The final page still features a man who looks suspiciously not <em>un</em>like Tony Abbott, but he’s joined by a priest, a judge, the queen, and – being helicoptered in – an extended family, all there to celebrate the wedding. “You-know-who arrived just in time,” it reads. </p> <p>Hopkins thinks the change is for the better: “I didn’t want too much of a political agenda,” she says. But the agenda is hard to miss. In fact, along with the time-sensitive nature of the project, it was part of the reason the pair chose to release it themselves, rather than going with a traditional publisher. </p> <p>“We both know from our experience that when you work in-house with a traditional publisher you get lots of different people involved – sales and marketing, all these kinds – and we just didn’t want that, and we didn’t have time for it.”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"87d96c124fe7312bdeb3067e59f8938ca40b1140\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/87d96c124fe7312bdeb3067e59f8938ca40b1140/0_0_2398_2757/870.jpg\" alt=\"Mummy and Mumma Get Married (2016)\" width=\"870\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Cover of Mummy and Mumma Get Married, which the authors say is Australia’s first picture book to address same-sex families.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Cara King/Captain Honey</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The book is clearly aimed at families of lesbian mums, but Hopkins and Winter always hoped it would reach a wider audience. Hopkins says it’s “just as important” for children of heteronormative families to be exposed to alternative family structures as it is for children of those alternative families. But while the publishers they approached for help with distribution were initially supportive, they didn’t end up helping. “I feel that publishers like to be seen to be associated with these [progressive titles], but they also know that they’re – how can I put this – they probably see them as niche.”<br /></p> <p>Instead, they went with a crowdfunding campaign, which raised $7,500 in 30 days, well above their $5,000 target. As part of the campaign, people could choose to buy a book themselves, donate one to a school library, or both. </p> <p>Not all of those schools were happy recipients. “One or two schools wrote to me saying they would refuse – ‘We will pass on the donation, thank you.’ A couple of Catholic schools,” Hopkins says. But a few supporters sent their books to Catholic schools regardless. “It wasn’t my idea!” she laughs. “But I’m sure there’ll be some feedback coming through about it soon.”</p> <p>As they endeavour to move the rest of their product, the pair plans to organise a speaking tour around secondary schools; they’ve put together 14 pages of teaching notes to go with it, too. “It just feels like momentum is going to keep building, with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/dec/30/maya-newell-2015-gayby-baby-we-learned-some-things-need-to-get-ugly-for-change\">the Gayby Baby controversy</a> at the end of last year, and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/feb/04/play-school-puts-out-casting-call-for-child-with-two-dads-to-show-diverse-families\">the Play School [casting call for gay parents]</a> this month,” Hopkins says. “The political aspect is being slowed down ... but marriage equality will, I think, happen as soon as it can happen. It feels like all the energy is moving in the right direction.”</p> <p>But a little nudge can’t hurt. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"9ecc85b4d5a466ba99f60bd7a0c8a0afe82183fb\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/9ecc85b4d5a466ba99f60bd7a0c8a0afe82183fb/0_0_2398_1381/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Spread from Mummy and Mumma Get Married\" width=\"1000\" height=\"576\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Spread from Mummy and Mumma Get Married by Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter, with illustrations by Cara King</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Cara King/Captain Honey</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <ul> <li><em>Mummy and Mumma Get Married is available through <a href=\"http://captainhoney.com.au/portfolio_page/mummy-and-mumma-get-married/\">Captain Honey</a></em></li> </ul>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ght4","wordcount":"986","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9ecc85b4d5a466ba99f60bd7a0c8a0afe82183fb/0_236_1088_654/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-02-20T03:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Mummy and Mumma Get Married follows a young girl who wants to surprise her parents with a wedding. The only thing stopping them is you-know-who</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/feb/17/this-is-australias-first-picture-book-about-same-sex-parenting-why-did-it-take-so-long","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/feb/17/this-is-australias-first-picture-book-about-same-sex-parenting-why-did-it-take-so-long","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"9ecc85b4d5a466ba99f60bd7a0c8a0afe82183fb","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9ecc85b4d5a466ba99f60bd7a0c8a0afe82183fb/8_132_1407_846/1000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/9ecc85b4d5a466ba99f60bd7a0c8a0afe82183fb","altText":"From Mummy and Mumma get Married (2016), by Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter. Illustrations are by Cara King.","caption":"From Mummy and Mumma get Married (2016), by Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter. Illustrations are by Cara King.","photographer":"Cara King","source":"