"id":"australia-news/australia-news","sectionId":"australia-news","webTitle":"Australia news","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/australia-news","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/australia-news/australia-news","sectionName":"Australia news","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/features","webTitle":"Features","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/features","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/features","references":[]},{"id":"profile/steph-harmon","webTitle":"Steph Harmon","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Steph Harmon is culture editor of Guardian Australia. Steph joined the Guardian after three years as founding editor of Australian pop culture/politics site <a href=\"http://junkee.com/\">Junkee.</a> Steph tweets <a href=\"https://twitter.com/stephharmon\">@stephharmon</a>. You can email her at <a href=\"mailto:steph.harmon@theguardian.com\">steph.harmon@theguardian.com</a></p>","bylineImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2016/1/8/1452243797516/Steph-Harmon.jpg","bylineLargeImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2016/1/8/1452243815679/Steph-Harmon-L.png","firstName":"steph","lastName":"harmon","twitterHandle":"stephharmon","r2ContributorId":"56794","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/steph-harmon","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/steph-harmon","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-17T03:41:19Z","webTitle":"Great children's picture books about same-sex parenting – in pictures","sectionId":"books","type":"gallery","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"books/gallery/2016/feb/17/great-childrens-picture-books-about-same-sex-parenting-in-pictures","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Roz Hopkins","headline":"Great children's picture books about same-sex parenting – in pictures","trailText":"Co-author of Australia’s Mummy and Mumma Get Married, Roz Hopkins, shares some of her favourite children’s books for alternative families","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"AUS","body":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"36b9e649928520ed9b0275b446ce901eace91e4c\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/36b9e649928520ed9b0275b446ce901eace91e4c/0_0_1054_1100/958.jpg\" alt=\"Cover of Heather Has Two Mummies by Leslea Newman\" width=\"958\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Heather Has Two Mommies by Leslea Newman was first published to considerable controversy in the US in 1989; it was re-released for its 25th anniversary in 2015. Walker Books published an Australian version of in 2015 too, in which the spelling of title was tweaked to Heather Has Two Mummies. <br><br>It’s a lovely story about a little girl and her schoolmates at playgroup describing their various families to each other. In the 25th-anniversary edition, there is one small, subtle change: the mummies now wear wedding rings.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Laura Cornell/Walker Books</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"2d7aaf8dab496334555bfbfe987a637947c1bffa\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/2d7aaf8dab496334555bfbfe987a637947c1bffa/0_0_498_500/498.jpg\" alt=\"Cover of Mommy, Mama and Me by Leslea Newman\" width=\"498\" height=\"500\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Leslea Newman also wrote Mommy, Mama, and Me (2009), in which a child goes about a range of everyday activities – having a snack, having a piggyback ride, hair being combed – with their two mums. I say ‘their’ because the book avoids identifying the child as male or female, which makes it great for parents of boys and girls. <br><br>It’s a very simple rhyming book, with simple illustrations – it’s for young readers. A strength is its focus on the everyday, which normalises having two mothers, rather than drawing attention to it. <br><br><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Daddy-Papa-Me-Lesl%C3%A9a-Newman/dp/1582462623\">Daddy, Papa and Me</a> was published that year too.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Carol Thompson/Tricycle Press</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"2fa0fa21e0d51d351e751f0fcab5d739187e1994\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/2fa0fa21e0d51d351e751f0fcab5d739187e1994/0_0_1024_1024/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Cover of It's Okay to be Different by Todd Parr\" width=\"1000\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">While not specifically on the same-sex theme, American author Todd Parr does a wonderful job of speaking to kids from different backgrounds with books such as It’s Okay to Be Different (2009) and <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Mommy-Book-Todd-Parr/dp/0316070440/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1455597113&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=todd+parr+the+mommy+book\">the Mommy Book</a> (2010). A lot of lesbian mums I know have cited these titles as important for teaching their children the value of difference. <br><br>What really appeals to me about Parr’s books are the bold, graphic illustration styles which – paired with short, simple text – make for an easy and fun way to get a message across.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Todd Parr/Little Brown</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3b83e1e2dbcbf1d990ce33483096becb3355ea57\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/3b83e1e2dbcbf1d990ce33483096becb3355ea57/0_0_2801_2782/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Cover of Stella Brings the Family, by Miriam B Schiffer and Holly Clifton-Brown\" width=\"1000\" height=\"993\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Stella Brings the Family, by Miriam B Schiffer and Holly Clifton-Brown, is an equivalent to Heather Has Two Mommies, but for children with gay dads. <br><br>In this story, a little girl struggles with how to respond when asked to bring her mother to school on Mother’s Day. She finds a great solution by bringing all the people who love her. <br><br>This is a sweet story about love and acceptance. It’s a great topic and one that early childhood educators and teachers should be mindful to consider. The illustrations are fresh and contemporary.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Holly Clifton-Brown/Chronicle Books</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"e4eb98e8b12a6f9208dd8739063f6e126bd44012\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/e4eb98e8b12a6f9208dd8739063f6e126bd44012/0_0_2978_2500/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Cover of and Tango Makes Three, by Justin Richardson and Peter Parnell\" width=\"1000\" height=\"839\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Taking a different tack is Justin Richardson and Peter Parnell’s and Tango Makes Three (2005), inspired by the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/nov/19/gayrights.usa\">true story</a> of a penguin family in New York’s Central Park zoo. Zookeepers gave the ‘in-love’ male couple a fertilised egg and they became dedicated daddies to their chick. <br><br>There is so much to commend this beautiful book. It’s been lovingly put together, and it’s a straightforward story about love. That it focuses on animals is a masterstroke in engaging the interest of children, and that it is based on a true story is magic. <br><br>A 10th anniversary edition with CD was released in 2015.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Henry Cole/Little Simon</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"87d96c124fe7312bdeb3067e59f8938ca40b1140\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/87d96c124fe7312bdeb3067e59f8938ca40b1140/0_0_2398_2757/870.jpg\" alt=\"Cover of Mummy and Mumma Get Married by Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter\" width=\"870\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Mummy and Mumma Get Married (2016), by Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter, with illustrations by Cara King. <a href=\"http://captainhoney.com.au/portfolio_page/mummy-and-mumma-get-married/\">Head here</a> for more information.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Cara King/Captain Honey</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4gncp","wordcount":"0","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/2d7aaf8dab496334555bfbfe987a637947c1bffa/0_149_498_298/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-02-20T03:45:00Z","standfirst":"<p>This year, after a hugely successful crowdfunding campaign, Australian couple Roz Hopkins and Natalie Winter released their first children’s book: Mummy and Mumma Get Married. It’s one of the only Australian picture books to specifically address same-sex parenting, a market gap that Hopkins believes speaks volumes for both Australia’s deeply competitive children’s book industry, and where the country is at on the issue. </p><p>Here, Hopkins shares some of her favourite international children’s books that deal with alternative families</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/gallery/2016/feb/17/great-childrens-picture-books-about-same-sex-parenting-in-pictures","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/gallery/2016/feb/17/great-childrens-picture-books-about-same-sex-parenting-in-pictures","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"36b9e649928520ed9b0275b446ce901eace91e4c","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets